Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:01.340
- I'm Sam O'Brien,

00:00:01.340 --> 00:00:03.410
I'm the Foods Editor at Atlas Obscura,

00:00:03.410 --> 00:00:06.670
and I'm here at the World Grits
Festival in South Carolina

00:00:06.670 --> 00:00:08.708
to participate in Rolling in the Grits.

00:00:08.708 --> 00:00:11.375
(intense music)

00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:26.750
For the Rolling in the Grits competition,

00:00:26.750 --> 00:00:29.240
the contestants each have 10 seconds

00:00:29.240 --> 00:00:31.993
to trap as many grits on
their body as possible.

00:00:33.190 --> 00:00:35.033
Should I mention the pool and stuff?

00:00:35.033 --> 00:00:37.080
(intense music)

00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:39.400
So the way the Rolling in
the Grits competition works

00:00:39.400 --> 00:00:43.880
is they fill a giant
kiddie pool with grits,

00:00:43.880 --> 00:00:46.490
it's about 550 pounds of dry grits

00:00:46.490 --> 00:00:49.020
and over 300 gallons of water,

00:00:49.020 --> 00:00:51.970
and each contestant dives
right into the pool,

00:00:51.970 --> 00:00:54.150
has 10 seconds to trap as much grits

00:00:54.150 --> 00:00:55.530
on their body as possible,

00:00:55.530 --> 00:00:57.230
and then they're weighed before and after

00:00:57.230 --> 00:00:59.230
to determine who trapped the most grits.

00:01:00.680 --> 00:01:02.283
- Our first place winner,

00:01:03.550 --> 00:01:07.828
coming in with 27 pounds of grits...

00:01:07.828 --> 00:01:10.495
(intense music)

00:01:14.624 --> 00:01:17.430
(clapping beat)

00:01:17.430 --> 00:01:18.390
- The World Grits Festival

00:01:18.390 --> 00:01:20.290
is a celebration of all things grits.

00:01:20.290 --> 00:01:21.510
There are grits you can eat,

00:01:21.510 --> 00:01:23.030
there are grits arts and crafts,

00:01:23.030 --> 00:01:25.480
and there are even grits
you can jump right into.

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:30.680
It all started in 1986,

00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:32.780
when the owner of a local Piggly Wiggly

00:01:32.780 --> 00:01:36.010
was ordering a massive amount
of grits from his supplier,

00:01:36.010 --> 00:01:38.267
and the supplier said
something along the lines of

00:01:38.267 --> 00:01:40.600
"You order more grits than anybody else."

00:01:40.600 --> 00:01:43.900
So he'd asked around
to his other suppliers

00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:45.490
and they said the same thing.

00:01:45.490 --> 00:01:46.620
So, according to the lore,

00:01:46.620 --> 00:01:50.170
he determined that St. George
consumed more grits per capita

00:01:50.170 --> 00:01:51.620
than other town in the world.

00:01:54.660 --> 00:01:56.640
They wanted something flashy and fun

00:01:56.640 --> 00:01:58.200
to attract people to the festival

00:01:58.200 --> 00:02:00.580
so they started the Rolling
in the Grits Competition

00:02:00.580 --> 00:02:03.193
the very first year the
festival kicked off in '86.

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:08.730
I first learned about
the contest last year,

00:02:08.730 --> 00:02:11.230
and since then I've
been a little obsessed.

00:02:11.230 --> 00:02:12.500
I'm really just the kind of person

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:14.550
who likes to prepare for
something before doing it.

00:02:14.550 --> 00:02:17.690
My first step was contacting
the world record holder,

00:02:17.690 --> 00:02:18.730
Tiffany McGirr,

00:02:18.730 --> 00:02:21.490
she trapped 66 pounds
of grits on her body,

00:02:21.490 --> 00:02:23.430
so I talked to her about her strategies,

00:02:23.430 --> 00:02:25.260
and asked her if she had any tips for me.

00:02:25.260 --> 00:02:26.950
She was super helpful.

00:02:26.950 --> 00:02:29.970
So, last week, before the competition,

00:02:29.970 --> 00:02:31.470
I went to my sister's house

00:02:31.470 --> 00:02:34.170
to try out a few of those techniques.

00:02:40.395 --> 00:02:43.312
(orchestral music)

00:02:59.892 --> 00:03:02.892
(air pump whirring)

00:03:06.442 --> 00:03:09.192
(grits sloshing)

00:03:21.651 --> 00:03:24.234
(tape peeling)

00:03:59.820 --> 00:04:01.840
- At first it felt a little weird,

00:04:01.840 --> 00:04:04.430
the consistency is definitely something

00:04:04.430 --> 00:04:06.230
you're not used to swimming through,

00:04:07.524 --> 00:04:10.220
but you get used to it really quickly

00:04:10.220 --> 00:04:13.120
and now I'm quite comfortable in here.

00:04:15.146 --> 00:04:16.870
It's not so bad.

00:04:16.870 --> 00:04:18.470
It's a little unnerving at first,

00:04:18.470 --> 00:04:19.990
but you get used to it.

00:04:19.990 --> 00:04:22.330
I feel more ready than I did previously,

00:04:22.330 --> 00:04:25.850
because I had never dove
into a pool of grits before,

00:04:25.850 --> 00:04:28.410
but I am a little nervous

00:04:28.410 --> 00:04:31.190
at how quickly the 10 seconds went by.

00:04:31.190 --> 00:04:32.330
I think I'm definitely gonna need

00:04:32.330 --> 00:04:35.150
to act faster than I thought,

00:04:35.150 --> 00:04:37.163
but I definitely feel more prepared now.

00:04:39.310 --> 00:04:40.680
- So that's why we give you the rules,

00:04:40.680 --> 00:04:42.640
to let you know at the beginning

00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:44.060
that no type of jewelry,

00:04:44.060 --> 00:04:46.040
